b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\n\n\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC " -//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\n\n<workbook_page id="p1a_energy_phase_change" xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\n    xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\n    xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\n    xmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/">\n\n\n    <head>\n        <title>Energy and Phase Changes</title>\n        <objref idref="heating_curve"/>\n\n    </head>\n\n    <body>\n\n        <section>\n            <title>Enthalpy of Vaporization</title>\n            <body>\n                <p>Vaporization is an endothermic process. The cooling effect can be evident when\n                    you leave a swimming pool or a shower. When the water on your skin evaporates,\n                    it removes heat from your skin and causes you to feel cold. The energy change\n                    associated with the vaporization process is the enthalpy of vaporization, \xce\x94<em\n                        style="italic">H</em><sub>vap</sub>. For example, the vaporization of water\n                    at standard temperature is represented by:</p>\n                <formula>$${\\mathrm H}_2\\mathrm O(l)\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;{\\mathrm H}_2\\mathrm\n                    O(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta\n                    H_\\mathrm{vap}\\;=\\;44.01\\;\\mathrm{kJ}/\\mathrm{mol}$$</formula>\n                <p>As described in the unit on thermochemistry, the reverse of an endothermic\n                    process is exothermic. And so, the condensation of a gas releases heat:</p>\n                <formula>$${\\mathrm H}_2\\mathrm O(g)\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;{\\mathrm H}_2\\mathrm\n                    O(l)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta H_\\mathrm{con}\\;=\\;-\\mathrm\\Delta\n                    H_\\mathrm{vap}=\\;-44.01\\;\\mathrm{kJ}/\\mathrm{mol}$$</formula>\n            </body>\n        </section>\n        <section>\n            <title> Enthalpy of Fusion</title>\n            <body>\n                <p>The amount of heat required to change one mole of a substance from the solid\n                    state to the liquid state is the enthalpy of fusion, \xce\x94<em style="italic"\n                        >H</em><sub>fus</sub> of the substance. The enthalpy of fusion of ice is 6.0\n                    kJ/mol at 0 \xc2\xb0C. Fusion (melting) is an endothermic process:</p>\n                <formula>$${\\mathrm H}_2\\mathrm O(s)\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;{\\mathrm H}_2\\mathrm\n                    O(l)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta\n                    H_\\mathrm{fus}\\;=\\;6.01\\;\\mathrm{kJ}/\\mathrm{mol}$$</formula>\n                <p>The reciprocal process, freezing, is an exothermic process whose enthalpy change\n                    is \xe2\x88\x926.0 kJ/mol at 0 \xc2\xb0C:</p>\n                <formula>$${\\mathrm H}_2\\mathrm O(l)\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;{\\mathrm H}_2\\mathrm\n                    O(s)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta H_\\mathrm{frz}\\;\\;=\\;-\\mathrm\\Delta\n                    H_\\mathrm{fus}\\;=\\;-6.01\\;\\mathrm{kJ}/\\mathrm{mol}$$</formula>\n            </body>\n        </section>\n        <example>\n            <p>One way our body is cooled is by evaporation of the water in sweat. In very hot\n                climates, we can lose as much as 1.5 L of sweat per day. Although sweat is not pure\n                water, we can get an approximate value of the amount of heat removed by evaporation\n                by assuming that it is. How much heat is required to evaporate 1.5 L of water (1.5\n                kg) at T = 37 \xc2\xb0C (normal body temperature); \xce\x94<em style="italic">H</em><sub>vap</sub>\n                = 43.46 kJ/mol at 37 \xc2\xb0C.</p>\n            <p>We start with the known volume of sweat (approximated as just water) and use the\n                given information to convert to the amount of heat needed:</p>\n\n            <formula>$$\\require{cancel}1.5\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm L}\\times\\frac{1000\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm\n                g}}{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm L}}\\times\\frac{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}}}{18\\cancel{\\;\\mathrm\n                g}}\\times\\frac{43.46\\;\\mathrm{kJ}}{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}}}\\;=\\;3.6\\times10^3\\;\\mathrm{kJ}$$</formula>\n            <p>Thus, 3600 kJ of heat are removed by the evaporation of 1.5 L of water.</p>\n        </example>\n        <wb:inline idref="ht_vap_digt" purpose="didigetthis"/>\n        <section>\n            <title>Enthalpy of Sublimation</title>\n            <body>\n                <p>Like vaporization, the process of sublimation requires an input of energy to\n                    overcome intermolecular attractions. The enthalpy of sublimation, \xce\x94<em\n                        style="italic">H</em><sub>sub</sub>, is the energy required to convert one\n                    mole of a substance from the solid to the gaseous state. For example, the\n                    sublimation of carbon dioxide is represented by:</p>\n                <formula>$${\\mathrm{CO}}_2(s)\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;{\\mathrm{CO}}_2(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta\n                    H_\\mathrm{sub}\\;=\\;26.1\\;\\mathrm{kJ}/\\mathrm{mol}$$</formula>\n\n                <p>Consider the extent to which intermolecular attractions must be overcome to\n                    achieve a given phase transition. Converting a solid into a liquid requires that\n                    these attractions be only partially overcome; transition to the gaseous state\n                    requires that they be completely overcome. As a result, the enthalpy of fusion\n                    for a substance is less than its enthalpy of vaporization. This same logic can\n                    be used to derive an approximate relation between the enthalpies of all phase\n                    changes for a given substance. Though not an entirely accurate description,\n                    sublimation may be conveniently modeled as a sequential two-step process of\n                    melting followed by vaporization in order to apply Hess\xe2\x80\x99s Law. Viewed in this\n                    manner, the enthalpy of sublimation for a substance may be estimated as the sum\n                    of its enthalpies of fusion and vaporization. For example:</p>\n                <formula>\n                    $$\\mathrm{solid}\\;\\;\\;\\rightarrow\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm{liquid}\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\triangle\n                    H_{\\mathrm{fus}}\\\\\\underline{\\mathrm{liquid}\\;\\;\\;\\rightarrow\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm{gas}\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\triangle\n                    H_{\\mathrm{vap}}}\\\\\\mathrm{solid}\\;\\;\\;\\rightarrow\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm{gas}\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\triangle\n                    H_{\\mathrm{sub}}\\;=\\;\\triangle H_{\\mathrm{fus}}\\;+\\;\\triangle H_{\\mathrm{vap}}$$ </formula>\n                <image src="../webcontent/CNX_Chem_10_03_PhaseChng.jpg"\n                    alt="A diagram is shown with a vertical line drawn on the left side and labeled \xe2\x80\x9cEnergy\xe2\x80\x9d and three horizontal lines drawn near the bottom, lower third and top of the diagram. These three lines are labeled, from bottom to top, \xe2\x80\x9cSolid,\xe2\x80\x9d \xe2\x80\x9cLiquid\xe2\x80\x9d and \xe2\x80\x9cGas.\xe2\x80\x9d Near the middle of the diagram, a vertical, upward-facing arrow is drawn from the solid line to the gas line and labeled \xe2\x80\x9cSublimation, delta sign, H, subscript sub.\xe2\x80\x9d To the right of this arrow is a second vertical, upward-facing arrow that is drawn from the solid line to the liquid line and labeled \xe2\x80\x9cFusion, delta sign, H, subscript fus.\xe2\x80\x9d Above the second arrow is a third arrow drawn from the liquid line to the gas line and labeled, \xe2\x80\x9cVaporization, delta sign, H, subscript vap.\xe2\x80\x9d"\n                    width="450">\n                    <caption>For a given substance, the sum of its enthalpy of fusion and enthalpy\n                        of vaporization is approximately equal to its enthalpy of\n                        sublimation.</caption>\n                </image>\n\n            </body>\n        </section>\n        <wb:inline idref="ht_vap2_digt" purpose="didigetthis"/>\n        <p>Adapted from <link href="https://cnx.org/contents/havxkyvS@9.422:b39avmGq@29/Preface"\n                >Openstax Chemistry </link>under <link\n                href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/"> Creative Commons Attribution\n                4.0 License. </link></p>\n        <p>Download for free at <link\n                href="http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312"\n                >http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312.</link></p>\n\n\n\n    </body>\n</workbook_page>\n'